## Pipeline Overview

A self-organizing team of agents. Each agent knows who to hand off to next based on the context it receives. Nothing ships without passing Bagnik.

```
Idea → Vadavik (spec) → Lojma (UX) + Veles (docs, parallel)
     → Cmok /skill/ (mockups) → User UAT
     → Laznik (arch + tests) → Bagnik (test gate)
     → Cmok /agent/ (build) + Veles (docs, parallel) → Bagnik (code QA)
     → Zlydni (commit + archive)
```

### Agents

| Agent   | Role                        | Model  |
|---------|-----------------------------|--------|
| Bagnik  | Test gate & code QA         | Opus   |
| Cmok    | Build                       | Sonnet |
| Veles  | Documentation               | Sonnet |
| Zlydni  | Commits & version control   | Haiku  |

### Skills

| Skill     | Role                          |
|-----------|-------------------------------|
| Vadavik   | Spec & requirements           |
| Lojma     | UX design                     |
| Cmok      | UX mockups                    |
| Laznik    | Architecture & tests          |

### Invocation

The kit uses the **same role names** in every IDE. What changes is only the **control** your editor exposes (slash menu, `@` rules, agent picker, and so on).

**Roles**

| Kind | Names |
|------|--------|
| **Skills** | `vadavik`, `lojma`, `laznik`, `cmok` (mockups only for `cmok`) |
| **Agents** | `bagnik`, `cmok` (implementation after gates), `veles`, `zlydni` |

**Mockups vs Cmok build:** the **skill** `cmok` is mockups only. **Implementation** after Bagnik is the **agent** `cmok` in Claude/Copilot; in Cursor that agent is exposed as the rule **`cmok-build`** so it does not clash with the **`cmok`** skill.

**How to invoke (by IDE)**

| IDE | Skills | Agents |
|-----|--------|--------|
| **Claude Code** | Slash in chat: **`/vadavik`**, **`/lojma`**, **`/laznik`**, **`/cmok`** | **`@bagnik`**, **`@cmok`**, **`@veles`**, **`@zlydni`**, or the Agent / subagent flow with those names |
| **Cursor** | In **Agent** chat, type **`/`** and pick the skill by name (discovered automatically; see [Agent Skills](https://cursor.com/docs/context/skills)). Optional: type **`/vadavik`**-style if your build resolves it the same way. | [Project rules](https://cursor.com/docs/context/rules): type **`@`** + rule basename to attach a rule explicitly, e.g. **`@bagnik`**, **`@cmok-build`**, **`@veles`**, **`@zlydni`**; kit agent rules use **Apply Intelligently** (`alwaysApply: false`), so the Agent can also include them **by relevance** from each rule’s description. Baseline protocol: root **`AGENTS.md`** plus the always-on **pipeline** rule. |
| **GitHub Copilot** (VS Code) | No Claude-style slash; workspace instructions apply broadly—refer to **Vadavik / Lojma / Laznik / Cmok** by name in the prompt. | Open the **agents** control in Copilot Chat and choose the workspace agent (**bagnik**, **cmok**, **veles**, **zlydni**); labels match each agent file’s `name:` field (see [Custom agents in VS Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/customization/custom-chat-modes)). If your build offers **`@`** participants for those agents, you can use the same names there. |

The **Handoff Map** below uses **`/…`** and **`@…`** as **short labels** for those same roles (Claude-style). Translate using the table above.

